TY  - JOUR
T1  - Perfectionism and Choice
AU  - Kopylov, Igor
Y1  - 2012/09/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8941
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1819
EP  - 1843
VL  - 80
IS  - 5
KW  - Flexibility
KW  - commitment
KW  - self-esteem
KW  - self-evaluation
KW  - compulsive shopping
KW  - task avoidance
KW  - guilt
KW  - Set-Betweenness
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8941
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Empirical evidence suggests that perfectionism can affect choice behavior. When striving for perfection, a person can desire to keep normatively appealing options feasible even if she persistently fails to use these options later. For instance, she can ?pay not to go to the gym,? as in DellaVigna and Malmendier (2006). By contrast, some perfectionists may avoid normatively important tasks for fear of negative self-evaluation of their performance. This paper models perfectionist behaviors in Gul and Pesendorfer's (2001) menu framework where agents may be tempted to deviate from their long-term normative objectives. In addition to self-control costs, I identify a utility component that reflects emotional costs and benefits of perfectionism. My model is derived from axioms imposed on preferences over menus in an essentially unique way.
ER  - 

