TY  - JOUR
T1  - Mechanism Design With Renegotiation and Costly Messages
AU  - Evans, Robert
Y1  - 2012/09/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8772
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 2089
EP  - 2104
VL  - 80
IS  - 5
KW  - Implementation with renegotiation
KW  - incomplete contracts
KW  - hold-up problem
KW  - communication costs
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8772
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - According to standard theory, the set of implementable efficient outcome functions is greatly reduced if the mechanism or contract can be renegotiated ex post. In some cases, contracts can achieve nothing and so, for example, the hold-up problem may be severe. This paper shows that if the mechanism is designed in such a way that sending a message involves a small cost, then renegotiation essentially does not restrict the set of efficient implementable functions. Given a weak preference-reversal condition, any Pareto-efficient, bounded social choice function can be implemented in subgame-perfect equilibrium in a renegotiation-proof manner, for any strictly positive message cost. The key point is that messages themselves can act as punishments.
ER  - 

