TY  - JOUR
T1  - Identification and Estimation of Average Partial Effects in “Irregular” Correlated Random Coefficient Panel Data Models
AU  - Graham, Bryan S.
AU  - Powell, James L.
Y1  - 2012/09/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8220
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 2105
EP  - 2152
VL  - 80
IS  - 5
KW  - Panel data
KW  - correlated random coefficients
KW  - semiparametric efficiency
KW  - irregularity
KW  - calorie demand
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8220
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In this paper we study identification and estimation of a correlated random coefficients (CRC) panel data model. The outcome of interest varies linearly with a vector of endogenous regressors. The coefficients on these regressors are heterogenous across units and may covary with them. We consider the average partial effect (APE) of a small change in the regressor vector on the outcome (cf. Chamberlain (1984), Wooldridge (2005a)). Chamberlain (1992) calculated the semiparametric efficiency bound for the APE in our model and proposed a √N-consistent estimator. Nonsingularity of the APE's information bound, and hence the appropriateness of Chamberlain's (1992) estimator, requires (i) the time dimension of the panel (T) to strictly exceed the number of random coefficients (p) and (ii) strong conditions on the time series properties of the regressor vector. We demonstrate irregular identification of the APE when T?=?p and for more persistent regressor processes. Our approach exploits the different identifying content of the subpopulations of stayers?or units whose regressor values change little across periods?and movers?or units whose regressor values change substantially across periods. We propose a feasible estimator based on our identification result and characterize its large sample properties. While irregularity precludes our estimator from attaining parametric rates of convergence, its limiting distribution is normal and inference is straightforward to conduct. Standard software may be used to compute point estimates and standard errors. We use our methods to estimate the average elasticity of calorie consumption with respect to total outlay for a sample of poor Nicaraguan households.
ER  - 

